{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}
<p>Expand each concept to check your understanding before the final unit.</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u09-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-u09-a", "Argument mapping — purpose and method") %}
  <p>Argument mapping makes the logical structure of an argument explicit through a visual diagram. Premises are connected by arrows to the claims they support; sub-conclusions feed into the main conclusion. Maps reveal whether premises are linked (jointly required), convergent (independently sufficient), or serial (chained).</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u09-b", "Three argument structures") %}
  <p><strong>Linked</strong>: premises work together — each is necessary. Remove one and the argument collapses. <strong>Convergent</strong>: each premise independently supports the conclusion. Removing one weakens but does not destroy the argument. <strong>Serial</strong>: a sub-conclusion at one stage becomes a premise at the next, forming a chain.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u09-c", "Critical evaluation — the ten-step framework") %}
  <p>1. Identify the main conclusion. 2. Identify premises. 3. Identify sub-conclusions. 4. Identify hidden assumptions. 5. Determine argument structure. 6. Evaluate truth of premises. 7. Evaluate strength of evidence. 8. Check for fallacies. 9. Evaluate validity or strength. 10. Evaluate soundness or cogency.</p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-u09-d", "Hidden assumptions — why do they matter?") %}
  <p>Every argument relies on unstated premises. If a hidden assumption is false, the argument fails even if all stated premises are true. Exposing hidden assumptions is especially important in inductive arguments, where the link between evidence and conclusion often involves significant background assumptions about representativeness, causation, or relevance.</p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

